# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bacterial-vaginosis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/acidity] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The condition is typically found in women between the ages of 35 and 50, but also affects younger women.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Patients with adenomyosis often present with painful menses (dysmenorrhea), profuse menses (menorrhagia), or both.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Other possible symptoms are pain during sexual intercourse, chronic pelvic pain and irritation of the urinary bladder.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] In adenomyosis, *basal* endometrium penetrates into hyperplastic myometrial fibers.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Unlike the functional layer, the basal layer does not undergo typical cyclic changes with the menstrual cycle.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Adenomyosis may involve the uterus focally, creating an adenomyoma.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] With diffuse involvement, the uterus becomes bulky and heavier.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Adenomyosis can be found together with endometriosis; it differs in that patients with endometriosis present endometrial-like tissue located entirely outside the uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] In endometriosis, the tissue is similar to, but not the same as, the endometrium.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The two conditions are found together in many cases yet often occur separately.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Before being recognized as a distinct condition, adenomyosis was called *endometriosis interna*.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The less-commonly-used term *adenomyometritis* is a more specific name for the condition, specifying involvement of the uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Adenomyosis can vary widely in the type and severity of symptoms that it causes, ranging from being entirely asymptomatic 33% of the time to being a severe and debilitating condition in some cases.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Women with adenomyosis typically first report symptoms when they are between 40 and 50, but symptoms can occur in younger women.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] It can be linked with endometriosis, but studies looking into similarities and differences between these two conditions have conflicting results.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The pathogenesis of adenomyosis still remains unclear, but the functioning of the inner myometrium, also called the junction zone (JZ), is believed to play a major role in the development of adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] It is also a matter of discussion whether the link between reproductive disorders and major obstetrical disorders also lies here.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Parity, age, and previous uterine abrasion increase the risk of adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Hormonal factors such as local hyperestrogenism and elevated levels of s-prolactin as well as autoimmune factors have also been identified as possible risk factors.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] As both the myometrium and stroma in an adenomyosis affected uterus show significant differences from those of a non-affected uterus, a complex origin that includes multifactorial changes on both genetic and biochemical levels is likely.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The tissue injury and repair (TIAR) theory is now widely accepted and suggests that uterine hyperperistalsis (i.e., increased peristalsis), during early periods of reproductive life will induce micro-injury at the endometrial-myometrial interface (EMI) region.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] That again leads to elevation of local estrogen in order to heal the damage.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] At the same time, estrogen treatment will increase uterine peristalsis again, leading to a vicious circle and a chain of biological alterations essential for the development of adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Iatrogenic injury of the junctional zone or physical damage due to placental implantation most likely results in the same pathological cascade.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Misplaced endometrial tissue proliferation in the myometrium causes symptoms through different mechanisms.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Uterine menstrual contractions are caused by prostaglandin, which is produced by normal endometrial tissue.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Dysmenorrhea is the main characteristic for this disease which are the result for high prostaglandin levels.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Endometrial proliferation is also led by estrogen; some treatments try to reduce its levels in order to decrease symptoms.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Adenomyosis patients present with heavy menstrual bleeding due to the increase of endometrial tissue, greater degree of vascularization, atypical uterine contractions and increased levels of prostaglandins, estrogen and eicosanoids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The diagnosis of adenomyosis is through a pathologist microscopically examining small tissue samples of the uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] These tissue samples can come from a uterine biopsy or directly following a hysterectomy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Uterine biopsies can be obtained by either a laparoscopic procedure through the abdomen or hysteroscopy through the vagina and cervix.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The diagnosis is established when the pathologist finds invading clusters of endometrial tissue within the myometrium.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Several diagnostic criterion can be used, but typically they require either the endometrial tissue to have invaded greater than 2% of the myometrium, or a minimum invasion depth between 2.5 and 8mm.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Adenomyosis can vary widely in the extent and location of its invasion within the uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] As a result, there are no established pathognomonic features to allow for a definitive diagnosis of adenomyosis through non-invasive imaging.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Nevertheless, non-invasive imaging techniques such as transvaginal ultrasonography (TVUS) and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) can both be used to strongly suggest the diagnosis of adenomyosis, guide treatment options, and monitor response to treatment.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Indeed, TVUS and MRI are the only two practical means available to establish a pre-surgical diagnosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Transvaginal ultrasonography is a cheap and readily available imaging test that is typically used early during the evaluation of gynecologic symptoms.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Ultrasound imaging, like MRI, does not use radiation and is safe for examination of the pelvis and female reproductive organs.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Overall, it is estimated that transvaginal ultrasonography has a sensitivity of 79% and specificity of 85% for the detection of adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Common transvaginal ultrasound findings are defined by the European MUSA group in 2015 and are defined in 2022 by the MUSA group.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The ultrasound characteristics can be divided in direct and indirect features.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The power Doppler or Doppler ultrasonography function can be used during transvaginal ultrasonography to help differentiate adenomyomas from uterine fibroids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] This is because uterine fibroids typically have blood vessels circling the fibroid's capsule.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] In contrast, adenomyomas are characterized by widespread blood vessels within the lesion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Doppler ultrasonography also serves to differentiate the static fluid within myometrial cysts from flowing blood within vessels.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The junction zone (JZ), or a small distinct hormone-dependent region at the endometrial-myometrial interface, may be assessed by three-dimensional transvaginal ultrasound (3D TVUS) and MRI.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Features of adenomyosis are disruption, thickening, enlargement or invasion of the junctional zone.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] There is no consensus about the actual histology of the junctional zone and a recent review showed that the ultrasound, MRI and histology all define and describe the junctional zone differently.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) provides slightly better diagnostic capability compared to TVUS, due to the increased ability of MRI to differentiate objectively between different types of soft tissue.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] This is possible with MRI's higher spatial and contrast resolution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Overall, it is estimated that MRI has a sensitivity of 74% and specificity of 91% for the detection of adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Diagnosis through MRI focuses predominately upon investigating the junctional zone.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The uterus will have a thickened junctional zone with darker/diminished signal on both T1 and T2 weighted sequences.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Three objective measures of the junctional zone can be used to diagnose adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] A junctional zone width being greater than 40% of the width of the myometrium.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Variability in the width of the junctional zone being greater than 5 mm.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Interspersed within the thickened, darker signal of the junctional zone, one will often see foci of hyperintensity (bright spots) on the T2 weighted scans representing small cystically dilatated glands or more acute sites of microhemorrhage.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] MRI is limited by other factors, but not by calcified uterine fibroids (as is ultrasound).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] In particular, MRI is better able to differentiate adenomyosis from multiple small uterine fibroids.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Adenomyosis can only be cured definitively with surgical removal of the uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] As adenomyosis is responsive to reproductive hormones, it reasonably abates following menopause when these hormones decrease.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] For women in their reproductive years, adenomyosis can typically be managed with the goals to provide pain relief, to restrict progression of the process, and to reduce significant menstrual bleeding.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Broadly speaking, surgical management of adenomyosis is split into two categories: uterine-sparing and non-uterine-sparing procedures.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Uterine-sparing procedures are surgical operations that do not include surgical removal of the uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Some uterine-sparing procedures have the benefit of improving fertility or retaining the ability to carry a pregnancy to term.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] In contrast, some uterine-sparing procedures worsen fertility or even result in complete sterility.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The impact of each procedure on a woman's fertility is of particular concern and typically guides the selection.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Non-uterine-sparing procedures, by definition, include surgical removal of the uterus and consequently they will all result in complete sterility.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Hysterectomy, or surgical removal of the uterus, has historically been the primary method of diagnosing and treating adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] It was especially popular in women who had completed their childbearing or in cases where fertility was not desired.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Today, there are many more medical and surgical interventions available.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] These treatments, such as hormonal therapy and endometrial ablation, have significantly reduced the number of women who require a hysterectomy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] That being said, hysterectomies remain as the final treatment option for women in whom the other treatments have failed.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Typically viewed as definitive treatment for the bleeding and pelvic pain associated with adenomyosis, a hysterectomy will always result in sterility and cessation of menstrual bleeding.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Pelvic pain, on the other hand, can persist after a hysterectomy in as many as 22% of women.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] There are many different types of hysterectomy, with varying options existing to removal the fallopian tubes, ovaries, and cervix.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Also, the varying types of hysterectomy can be performed by many different surgical techniques.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Variants also exist which combine several of these techniques and surgeries can even change during the operation from one technique to another in response to unforeseen obstacles or individual anatomy considerations.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] For example, adenomyosis can increase the size of the uterus to such an extent that it physically cannot be removed through the vagina without first being cut into smaller pieces.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Recent data suggest a prevalence of 20 to 35%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Adenomyosis is an often progressing condition.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] It is advocated that adenomyosis poses no increased risk for cancer development.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] However, both entities could coexist and the endometrial tissue within the myometrium could harbor endometrioid adenocarcinoma, with potentially deep myometrial invasion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Preterm labour and premature rupture of membranes both occur more frequently in women with adenomyosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] In sub-fertile women who received in-vitro fertilization (IVF), women with adenomyosis were less likely to become pregnant and subsequently more likely to experience a miscarriage.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] Given this, it is encouraged to screen women for adenomyosis by TVUS or MRI before starting assisted reproduction treatments (ART).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adenomyosis] The term *adenomyosis* is derived from the Greek terms *adeno-* (meaning *gland*), *myo-* (meaning *muscle*), and *-osis* (meaning *condition*).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adnexa-of-uterus] The **uterine appendages** (or **adnexa of uterus**) are the structures most closely related structurally and functionally to the uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adnexa-of-uterus] The term "adnexitis" is sometimes used to describe an inflammation of the uterine appendages (adnexa).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adnexa-of-uterus] In this context, it replaces the terms oophoritis and salpingitis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adnexa-of-uterus] The term adnexal mass is sometimes used when the location of a uterine mass is not yet more precisely known.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adnexa-of-uterus] 63% of ectopic pregnancies present with an adnexal mass.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adnexa-of-uterus] Depending on the size of the mass, it could be a medical emergency.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/adnexa-of-uterus] The term "adnexectomy" in gynaecology is often used for salpingo-oophorectomy (removal of both: fallopian tubes and ovaries).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] It is the aerobic counterpart of bacterial vaginosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The lack of acknowledgement of the difference between the two conditions might have led to inaccurate conclusions in several studies in the past.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The entity that has been described as "desquamative inflammatory vaginitis" probably corresponds to the more severe forms of aerobic vaginitis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Women with aerobic vaginitis usually have a thinned reddish vaginal mucosa, sometimes with extensive erosions or ulcerations and abundant yellowish discharge (without the fishy amine odour, typical of bacterial vaginosis).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Discharge is not always typical, and can range from sticky green/yellow to excessive and watery.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The pH can be high, but can also be within normal range, making it an unreliable indicator for infection.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Symptoms can include burning, stinging and dyspareunia.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Symptoms typically improve during menstruation, and flare afterwards.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The symptoms can last for long periods, sometimes even years.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Typically, patients have been treated several times with antimycotic and antibiotic drugs without relief.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] In asymptomatic cases, there is microscopic evidence but no symptoms.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The prevalence of asymptomatic cases is unknown.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The diagnosis is based on microscopic criteria.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Ideally, phase-contrast microscopy is used with a magnification of 400x (high-power field) or by Gram stain.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The "AV score" is calculated according to what is described in the table.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] pH measurement alone is not enough for the diagnosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Treatment is not always easy and aims at correcting the three key changes encountered in aerobic vaginitis: the presence of atrophy, inflammation and abnormal flora.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The treatment can include topical steroids to diminish the inflammation and topical estrogen to reduce the atrophy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The use and choice of antibiotics to diminish the load/proportion of aerobic bacteria is still a matter of debate.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] The use of local antibiotics, preferably local non-absorbed and broad-spectrum, covering enteric gram-positive and gram-negative aerobes, like kanamycin, can be an option.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] In some cases, systemic antibiotics can be helpful, such as Amoxicillin/clavulanic acidor moxifloxacin.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Vaginal rinsing with povidone iodine can provide rapid relief of symptoms but does not provide long-term reduction of bacterial loads.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Dequalinium chloride can also be an option for treatment.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] More recently, evidence of natural remedies such as topical herbal medicine, combined with biofilm disrupters such as EDTA, has proven successful in cases of aerobic vaginitis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Biofilms prove yet another hurdle when treating aerobic vaginitis, especially in chronic cases.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Topical biofilm disrupters, such as EDTA, can be useful, with systemic biofilm disrupters such as Serralase also having evidence of helping to disrupt bacterial biofilms, and helping to treat this condition.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] About 5 to 10% of women are affected by aerobic vaginitis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] Reports in pregnant women point to a prevalence of 8.3–10.8%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/aerobic-vaginitis] When considering symptomatic women, the prevalence of AV can be as high as 23%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Female fertility is heavily influenced by age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Fecundity generally remains consistent from a woman's late teens to her early thirties, after which it gradually declines.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The rate of decline accelerates after age 35, and by age 45, the natural non-conception rate ranges between 50% and 80%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] While menopause, or the permanent cessation of menstrual periods, generally occurs between ages 45 and 55 to signal the end of biological fertility, age-related infertility frequently occurs years prior.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The average age of a girl's first period (menarche) is 12 to 13 with regional variations: 12.5 years in the United States, 12.72 in Canada, 12.9 in the UK).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] In the first year post-menarche, around 80% of cycles are anovulatory.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] This declines to 50% in the third year, and to 10% by the sixth.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Little is known about fertility in young adolescents, as early teenage pregnancies are uncommon in most societies.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Female fertility generally peaks between the late teens and late twenties, after which it starts to decline.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] However, the probability of conception at a specific age varies between sources and is subject to debate.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] According to the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE), over 80% of women aged under 40 who have regular unprotected sexual intercourse will become pregnant within one year of trying.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] In the second year this percentage rises to over 90%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] According to a study done on a sample of 782 healthy European couples aged 19–39, fertility starts declining after age 27 and drops at a somewhat greater rate after age 35.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Statistical analysis showed that the women in the 27–29 age group had a significantly lower chance on average of becoming pregnant than did the 19–26-year-olds.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Pregnancy rates did not change notably between the 27–29 age group and the 30–34 age group, but dropped significantly for the 35–39 age group.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The age of the male partner had a significant impact on female fertility among the women who had reached their mid-30s, but not among the younger women.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] However, experts said the new study was too small and there were many variables that were too difficult to sort out, for a clear conclusion to be drawn.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Some experts suggested that the main change in fertility in older women was that it took them *longer* to conceive, not necessarily that they were significantly less likely to eventually succeed.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] David Dunson, a biostatistician at the U.S.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences, said that: "Although we noted a decline in female fertility in the late 20s, what we found was a decrease in the probability of becoming pregnant per menstrual cycle, not in the probability of eventually achieving a pregnancy".
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] A French study found no difference between the fertility rate of women under 25 and those aged 26–30, after which fertility started to decrease.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Estimating the "fertility of a woman" is quite difficult because of the male factor (quality of sperm).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] This French study looked at 2,193 women who were using artificial insemination because their husbands were azoospermic.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The cumulative success rates after 12 cycles of insemination were 73% for women under age 25, 74% in women ages 26–30, 61% for ages 31–35, and 54% in the over 35 age group.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] In Hungary, a study by the Központi Statisztikai Hivatal (Central Statistics Office) estimated that 7–12% of Hungarian women younger than 30 were infertile; 13–22% of women age 35 were infertile; and 24–46% of women age 40 were infertile.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The following is a table containing estimates of the percentage of women who will fail to obtain a live birth by the age of the woman when she starts trying to conceive.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Note that while for the young ages researchers tend to agree, for older ages there is discrepancy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] In terms of ovarian reserve, a typical woman has 12% of her reserve at age 30 and has only 3% at age 40.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] 81% of variation in ovarian reserve is due to age alone, making age the most important factor in female infertility.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The most common methods of checking the status of the ovarian reserve are to perform a blood test on day 3 of the menstrual cycle to measure serum follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) level.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Alternatively, a blood test to measure the serum anti-müllerian hormone (AMH) level can give similar information.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Transvaginal ultrasound can also be used to "count the number of follicles" and this procedure is called antral Follicle Count.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] A poor result from ovarian reserve testing does not signify an absolute inability to conceive and should not be the sole criterion considered to limit or deny access to infertility treatment.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] A study of a population of French women from 1670 and 1789 shows that those who married at age 20–24 had 7.0 children on average and 3.7% remained childless.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Women who married at age 25–29 years had a mean of 5.7 children and 5.0% remained childless.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Women who married at 30–34 years had a mean of 4.0 children and 8.2% remained childless.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The average age at last birth in natural fertility populations that have been studied is around 40.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] In 1957, a study was done on a large population (American Hutterites) that never used birth control.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The investigators measured the relationship between the age of the female partner and fertility.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The inverse correlation between age and female fertility in later reproductive life is argued to motivate family planning prior to reaching 35 years of age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The mapping of a woman's ovarian reserve, follicular dynamics and associated biomarkers can give an individual prognosis about future probabilities of pregnancy, thus facilitating an informed choice.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Especially since certain hormones can affect natural fertility.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Notably, in women aged 30–44 aiming to conceive spontaneously, a higher level of anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) has been positively correlated with increased fertility post-age related adjustment.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Thus, AMH measurements are helpful indicators for the estimation of the length of the fertile window.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] It is recommended that women have an infertility evaluation if they are over the age of 40 and planning to have a child, or if they are older than 35 and have not become pregnant after trying for a minimum of six months.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Infertility can be treated with reproductive technologies, which can be discussed with a qualified fertility specialist such as a reproductive endocrinologist.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] One such technology is *In Vitro* Fertilization (IVF), which is an assisted reproductive technology used to treat infertility.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] While many older women may opt for IVF treatment, patients with higher maternal age (>40 years old) have been found to have worse outcomes and a higher miscarriage rate compared to those aged 20–30.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Most IVF centers will attempt to use the patient's *own eggs* until approximately ages 43–45.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Clinically reproductive endocrinologists also tend to pursue IVF more aggressively in women over 35.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Another fertility procedure is Oocyte cryopreservation (egg freezing), which involves the preservation of oocytes by freezing them.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] These can then be thawed, fertilised, and transferred to the uterus through IVF.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] This gives women the ability to delay pregnancy while avoiding the infertility issues that arise from germ cell deterioration.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Studies show no increased risk of congenital abnormalities in children born from ova that have been cryopreserved, and IVF from thawed eggs has a comparable successful implantation rate to eggs that have never been frozen.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] While chromosomal abnormalities are avoided with egg freezing, pregnancy at older age increases the risk of gestational diabetes, preeclampsia, preterm labor, and cesarean section regardless of conception method.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] However, this field of reproductive technology is still developing and therapeutic interventions to halt or reverse the process of reproductive ageing in women is limited, despite the potential of stem cells which may be used to restore the ovarian reserve.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The age of the mother is a risk factor for a number of conditions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Pregnant women over 35 years of age are at increased risk for hypertension during pregnancy, eclampsia (hypertension during pregnancy with seizures), and gestational diabetes.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Furthermore, there is also a greater risk for delivery complications, including stillbirth, miscarriage, and complications leading to delivery via caesarean section.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Fetal complications are also high for women of advanced maternal age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] According to the Academy of Obstetrics and Gynecology, the risk for Down syndrome increases proportionally to maternal age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Other complications in women of advanced maternal age can include cardiac issues, esophageal atresia, hypospadias, and craniosynostosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] Finally, there is also an increased risk for premature birth and babies with low birth weight.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The capability to repair DNA strand breaks decreases with age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The repair pathway involves BRCA1 protein (breast cancer type 1 susceptibility protein) and ATM (ataxia–telangiectasia mutated) serine/threonine kinase.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] The specific DNA repair pathway affected by age is the homologous recombination DNA repair pathway.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] In general, women with BRCA1 mutations have lower ovarian reserves and experience earlier menopause.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/age-and-female-fertility] In mice, some delay of ovarian aging after treatment was shown.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] In chemistry, an **alkali** (/ˈælkəlaɪ/ ⓘ; from the Arabic word *al-qaly*, القالِي "saltwort") also **base** is a hydroxide of any of either the alkali metal which are Group I s-block elements, or the alkaline earth metal which are Group II s-block.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] *Alkali* can also be defined as a base that dissolves in water.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] A solution of a soluble base has a pH greater than 7.0.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] The adjectives ***alkaline*** and, less often, ***alkalescent*** are commonly used in English as a synonyms for *basic*, especially for bases soluble in water.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] This broad use of the term is likely to have come about because alkalis were the first bases known to obey the Arrhenius definition of a base, and they are still among the most common bases.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] The word *alkali* is derived from Arabic *al qalīy* (or *alkali*), meaning 'the calcined ashes' (see calcination), referring to the original source of alkaline substances.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] A water-extract of burned plant ashes, called *potash* and composed mostly of potassium carbonate, was mildly basic.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] After heating this substance with calcium hydroxide (*slaked lime*), a far more strongly basic substance known as *caustic potash* (potassium hydroxide) was produced.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] Caustic potash was traditionally used in conjunction with animal fats to produce soft soaps, one of the caustic processes that rendered soaps from fats in the process of saponification, one known since antiquity.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] Plant potash lent the name to the element potassium, which was first derived from caustic potash, and also gave potassium its chemical symbol **K** (from the German name *Kalium*), which ultimately derived from al**k**ali.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] Alkalis are all Arrhenius bases, ones which form hydroxide ions (OH−) when dissolved in water.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] The terms "base" and "alkali" are often used interchangeably, particularly outside the context of chemistry and chemical engineering.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] There are various, more specific definitions for the concept of an alkali.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] Alkalis are usually defined as a subset of the bases.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] The second subset of bases is also called an "Arrhenius base".
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] Soils with pH values that are higher than 7.3 are usually defined as being alkaline.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] These soils can occur naturally due to the presence of alkali salts.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] Although many plants do prefer slightly basic soil (including vegetables like cabbage and fodder like buffalo grass), most plants prefer mildly acidic soil (with pHs between 6.0 and 6.8), and alkaline soils can cause problems.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/alkali] In alkali lakes (also called *soda lakes*), evaporation concentrates the naturally occurring carbonate salts, giving rise to an alkalic and often saline lake.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Amenorrhea is a symptom with many potential causes.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Primary amenorrhea is defined as an absence of secondary sexual characteristics by age 13 with no menarche or normal secondary sexual characteristics but no menarche by 15 years of age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] It may be caused by developmental problems, such as the congenital absence of the uterus, failure of the ovary to receive or maintain egg cells, or delay in pubertal development.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Secondary amenorrhea, ceasing of menstrual cycles after menarche, is defined as the absence of menses for three months in a woman with previously normal menstruation, or six months for women with a history of oligomenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] It is often caused by hormonal disturbances from the hypothalamus and the pituitary gland, premature menopause, intrauterine scar formation, or eating disorders.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although amenorrhea has multiple potential causes, ultimately, it is the result of a hormonal imbalance or an anatomical abnormality.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Physiologically, menstruation is controlled by the release of gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) from the hypothalamus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] GnRH acts on the pituitary to stimulate the release of follicle stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] FSH and LH then act on the ovaries to stimulate the production of estrogen and progesterone which, respectively, control the proliferative and secretary phases of the menstrual cycle.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Prolactin also influences the menstrual cycle as it suppresses the release of LH and FSH from the pituitary.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Similarly, thyroid hormone also affects the menstrual cycle.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Low levels of thyroid hormone stimulate the release of TRH from the hypothalamus, which in turn increases both TSH and prolactin release.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] This increase in prolactin suppresses the release of LH and FSH through a negative feedback mechanism.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Amenorrhea can be caused by any mechanism that disrupts this hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarian axis, whether that it be by hormonal imbalance or by disruption of feedback mechanisms.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Amenorrhea is classified as either primary or secondary.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Primary amenorrhea is the absence of menstruation in a woman by the age of 16.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Females who have not reached menarche at 14 and who have no signs of secondary sexual characteristics (thelarche or pubarche) are also considered to have primary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Examples of amenorrhea include constitutional delay of puberty, Turner syndrome, and Mayer–Rokitansky–Küster–Hauser (MRKH) syndrome.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] It produces the appearance of secondary sexual characteristics, which are the sprouting of pubic and armpit hair, development of the breasts, and a lack of definition in the female body structure, such as the waist and hips.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Secondary amenorrhea is defined as the absence of menstruation for three months in a woman with a history of regular cyclic bleeding or six months in a woman with a history of irregular menstrual periods.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Examples of secondary amenorrhea include hypothyroidism, hyperthyroidism, hyperprolactinemia, polycystic ovarian syndrome, primary ovarian insufficiency, and functional hypothalamic amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Turner syndrome, monosomy 45XO, is a genetic disorder characterized by a missing, or partially missing, X chromosome.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Turner syndrome is associated with a wide spectrum of features that vary with each case.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] However, one common feature of this syndrome is ovarian insufficiency due to gonadal dysgenesis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Most people with Turner syndrome experience ovarian insufficiency within the first few years of life, before menarche.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Therefore, most patients with Turner syndrome will have primary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] However, the incidence of spontaneous puberty varies between 8–40% depending on whether or not there is a complete or partial absence of the X chromosome.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] MRKH (Mayer–Rokitansky–Küster–Hauser) syndrome is the second-most common cause of primary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] The syndrome is characterized by Müllerian agenesis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] In MRKH Syndrome, the Müllerian ducts develop abnormally and result in the absence of a uterus and cervix.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Even though patients with MRKH have functioning ovaries and therefore have secondary sexual characteristics, they experience primary amenorrhea since there is no functioning uterus.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Individuals with a female phenotype can present with primary amenorrhea due to complete androgen insensitivity syndrome (CAIS), 5-alpha-reductase 2 deficiency, pure gonadal dysgenesis, 17β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase deficiency, and mixed gonadal dysgenesis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Constitutional delay of puberty is a diagnosis of exclusion that is made when the workup for primary amenorrhea does not reveal another cause.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Constitutional delay of puberty is not due to a pathologic cause.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] It is considered a variant of the timeline of puberty.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although more common in boys, girls with delayed puberty present with the onset of secondary sexual characteristics after the age of 14, as well as menarche after the age of 16.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] This may be due to genetics, as some cases of constitutional delay of puberty are familial.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Physiologic amenorrhea is present before menarche, during pregnancy and breastfeeding, and after menopause.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Breastfeeding or lactational amenorrhea is also a common cause of secondary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Lactational amenorrhea is due to the presence of elevated prolactin and low levels of LH, which suppress ovarian hormone secretion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Breastfeeding typically prolongs postpartum lactational amenorrhea, and the duration of amenorrhea varies depending on how often a woman breastfeeds.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Due to this reason, breastfeeding has been advocated as a method of family planning, especially in developing countries where access to other methods of contraception may be limited.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Disturbances in thyroid hormone regulation have been a known cause of menstrual irregularities, including secondary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Patients with hypothyroidism frequently present with changes in their menstrual cycle.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] It is hypothesized that this is due to increased TRH, which goes on to stimulate the release of both TSH and prolactin.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Increased prolactin inhibits the release of LH and FSH, which are needed for ovulation to occur.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Patients with hyperthyroidism may also present with oligomenorrhea or amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Sex hormone binding globulin is increased in hyperthyroid states.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] This, in turn, increases the total levels of testosterone and estradiol.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Increased levels of LH and FSH have also been reported in patients with hyperthyroidism.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Changes in the hypothalamic-pituitary axis is a common cause of secondary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] GnRH is released from the hypothalamus and stimulates the anterior pituitary to release FSH and LH, which in turn stimulate the ovaries to release estrogen and progesterone.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Any pathology in the hypothalamus or pituitary can alter the way this feedback mechanism works and can cause secondary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Pituitary adenomas are a common cause of amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Prolactin secreting pituitary adenomas cause amenorrhea due to the hyper-secretion of prolactin which inhibits FSH and LH release.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Other space-occupying pituitary lesions can also cause amenorrhea due to the inhibition of dopamine, an inhibitor of prolactin, due to compression of the pituitary gland.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is a common endocrine disorder affecting 4–8% of women worldwide.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] It is characterized by multiple cysts on the ovary, amenorrhea or oligomenorrhea, and increased androgens.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although the exact cause remains unknown, it is hypothesized that increased levels of circulating androgens is what results in secondary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] PCOS may also be a cause of primary amenorrhea if androgen access is present prior to menarche.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although multiple cysts on the ovary are characteristic of the syndrome, this has not been noted to be a cause of the disease.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Women who perform excessive exercise regularly or lose a significant amount of weight are at risk of developing hypothalamic amenorrhea or exercise amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Functional hypothalamic amenorrhea (FHA) can be caused by stress, weight loss, or excessive exercise.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Many women who diet or who exercise at a high level do not take in enough calories to maintain their normal menstrual cycles.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] The threshold of developing amenorrhea appears to be dependent on low energy availability rather than absolute weight because a critical minimum amount of stored, easily mobilized energy is necessary to maintain regular menstrual cycles.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Amenorrhea is often associated with anorexia nervosa and other eating disorders.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Relative energy deficiency in sport, also known as the female athlete triad, is when a woman experiences amenorrhea, disordered eating, and osteoporosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Energy imbalance and weight loss can disrupt menstrual cycles through several hormonal mechanisms.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Weight loss can cause elevations in the hormone ghrelin which inhibits the hypothalamic-pituitary-ovarial axis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Elevated concentrations of ghrelin alter the amplitude of GnRH pulses, which causes diminished pituitary release of LH and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Low levels of the hormone leptin are also seen in females with low body weight.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Like ghrelin, leptin signals energy balance and fat stores to the reproductive axis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Decreased levels of leptin are closely related to low levels of body fat and correlate with a slowing of GnRH pulsing.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Certain medications, particularly contraceptive medications, can induce amenorrhea in a healthy woman.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] The lack of menstruation usually begins shortly after beginning the medication and can take up to a year to resume after stopping its use.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Hormonal contraceptives that contain only progestogen, like the oral contraceptive Micronor, and especially higher-dose formulations, such as the injectable Depo-Provera, commonly induce this side effect.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Extended cycle use of combined hormonal contraceptives also allow suppression of menstruation.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Patients who stop using combined oral contraceptive pills (COCP) may experience secondary amenorrhea as a withdrawal symptom.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] The link is not well understood, as studies have found no difference in hormone levels between women who develop amenorrhea as a withdrawal symptom following the cessation of COCP use and women who experience secondary amenorrhea because of other reasons.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] New contraceptive pills which do not have the normal seven days of placebo pills in each cycle, have been shown to increase rates of amenorrhea in women.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Studies show that women are most likely to experience amenorrhea after one year of treatment with continuous OCP use.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] The use of opiates (such as heroin) regularly has also been known to cause amenorrhea in long-term users.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Anti-psychotic drugs, which are commonly used to treat schizophrenia, have been known to cause amenorrhea as well.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Research suggests that anti-psychotic medications affect levels of prolactin, insulin, FSH, LH, and testosterone.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Recent research suggests that adding a dosage of metformin to an anti-psychotic drug regimen can restore menstruation.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Metformin has been shown to decrease resistance to the hormone insulin, as well as levels of prolactin, testosterone, and luteinizing hormone (LH).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Primary ovarian insufficiency (POI) affects 1% of females and is defined as the loss of ovarian function before the age of 40.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although the cause of POI can vary, it has been linked to chromosomal abnormalities, chemotherapy, and autoimmune conditions.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Hormone levels in POI are similar to menopause and are categorized by low estradiol and high levels of gonadotropins.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Since the pathogenesis of POI involves the depletion of ovarian reserve, restoration of menstrual cycles typically does not occur in this form of secondary amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Primary amenorrhea can be diagnosed in female children by age 14 if no secondary sex characteristics, such as enlarged breasts and body hair, are present.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] In the absence of secondary sex characteristics, the most common cause of amenorrhea is low levels of FSH and LH caused by a delay in puberty.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Gonadal dysgenesis, often associated with Turner syndrome, or premature ovarian failure may also be to blame.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] If secondary sex characteristics are present, but menstruation is not, primary amenorrhea can be diagnosed by age 16.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Evaluation of primary amenorrhea begins with a pregnancy test, prolactin, FSH, LH, and TSH levels.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Abnormal TSH levels prompt evaluation for hyper- and hypo-thyroidism with additional thyroid function tests.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Elevated prolactin levels prompt evaluation of the pituitary with an MRI to assess for any masses or malignancies.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] A pelvic ultrasound can also be obtained in the initial evaluation.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] If a uterus is not present on ultrasound, karyotype analysis and testosterone levels are obtained to assess for MRKH or androgen insensitivity syndrome.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] If a uterus is present, LH and FSH levels are used to make a diagnosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Low levels of LH and FSH suggest delayed puberty or functional hypothalamic amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Elevated levels of FSH and LH suggest primary ovarian insufficiency, typically due to Turner syndrome.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Normal levels of FSH and LH can suggest an anatomical outflow obstruction.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Secondary amenorrhea's most common and most easily diagnosable causes are pregnancy, thyroid disease, and hyperprolactinemia.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] A pregnancy test is a common first step for diagnosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Similar to primary amenorrhea, evaluation of secondary amenorrhea also begins with a pregnancy test, prolactin, FSH, LH, and TSH levels.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Abnormal TSH should prompt a thyroid workup with a full thyroid function test panel.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Elevated prolactin should be followed with an MRI to look for masses.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] If LH and FSH are elevated, menopause or primary ovarian insufficiency should be considered.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Normal or low levels of FSH and LH prompt further evaluation with patient history and the physical exam.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Testosterone, DHEA-S, and 17-hydroxyprogesterone levels should be obtained if there is evidence of excess androgens, such as hirsutism or acne.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] 17-hydroxyprogesterone is elevated in congenital adrenal hyperplasia.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Elevated testosterone and amenorrhea can suggest PCOS.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Elevated androgens can also be present in ovarian or adrenal tumors, so additional imaging may also be needed.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] History of disordered eating or excessive exercise should raise concern for hypothalamic amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Headache, vomiting, and vision changes can be signs of a tumor and needs evaluation with MRI.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Finally, a history of gynecologic procedures should lead to evaluation of Asherman syndrome with a hysteroscopy or progesterone withdrawal bleeding test.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Treatment for amenorrhea varies based on the underlying condition.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Treatment not only focuses on restoring menstruation, if possible, but also preventing additional complications associated with the underlying cause of amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] In primary amenorrhea, the goal is to continue pubertal development, if possible.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] For example, most patients with Turner syndrome will be infertile due to gonadal dysgenesis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] However, patients are frequently prescribed growth hormone therapy and estrogen supplementation to achieve taller stature and prevent osteoporosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] In other cases, such as MRKH, hormones do not need to be prescribed since the ovaries are able to function normally.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Patients with constitutional delay of puberty may be monitored by an endocrinologist, but definitive treatment may not be needed as there will eventually be progression to normal puberty.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Treatment for secondary amenorrhea varies greatly based on the root cause.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Functional hypothalamic amenorrhea is typically treated by weight gain through increased calorie intake and decreased expenditure.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Multidisciplinary treatment with monitoring from a physician, dietitian, and mental health counselor is recommended, along with support from family, friends, and coaches.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although oral contraceptives can cause menses to return, oral contraceptives should not be the initial treatment as they can mask the underlying problem and allow other effects of the eating disorder, like osteoporosis, to continue to develop.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Patients with hyperprolactinemia are often treated with dopamine agonists to reduce the levels of prolactin and restore menstruation.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Surgery and radiation may also be considered if dopamine agonists, such as cabergoline and bromocriptine, are ineffective.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Once prolactin levels are lowered, the resulting secondary amenorrhea is typically resolved.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Similarly, treatment of thyroid abnormalities often resolves the associated amenorrhea.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] For example, administration of thyroxine in patients with low thyroid levels restored normal menstruation in a majority of patients.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although there is currently no definitive treatment for PCOS, various interventions are used to restore more frequent ovulation in patients.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Weight loss and exercise have been associated with a return of ovulation in patients with PCOS due to normalization of androgen levels.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Metformin has also been recently studied to regularize menstrual cycles in patients with PCOS.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Although the exact mechanism remains unknown, it is hypothesized that this is due to metformin's ability to increase the body's sensitivity to insulin.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Anti-androgen medications, such as spironolactone, can also be used to lower body androgen levels and restore menstruation.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/amenorrhea] Oral contraceptive pills are also often prescribed to patients with secondary amenorrhea due to PCOS to regularize the menstrual cycle, although this is due to the suppression of ovulation.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is caused by an imbalance of the naturally occurring bacteria in the vagina.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] There is a change in the most common type of bacteria and a hundred to thousandfold increase in total numbers of bacteria present.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Typically, bacteria other than *Lactobacilli* become more common.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Risk factors include douching, new or multiple sex partners, antibiotics, and using an intrauterine device, among others.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] However, it is not considered a sexually transmitted infection and, unlike gonorrhoea and chlamydia, sexual partners are not treated.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Diagnosis is suspected based on the symptoms, and may be verified by testing the vaginal discharge and finding a higher than normal vaginal pH, and large numbers of bacteria.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is often confused with a vaginal yeast infection or infection with *Trichomonas*.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Usually treatment is with an antibiotic, such as clindamycin or metronidazole.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] These medications may also be used in the second or third trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The antiseptic boric acid can also be effective.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Probiotics may help prevent re-occurrence.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] It is unclear if the use of probiotics or antibiotics affects pregnancy outcomes.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is the most common vaginal infection in women of reproductive age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Prevalence differs by countries and demographics, with a systematic review and meta-analysis finding global prevalence in reproductive aged women ranges from 23 to 29%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] While BV-like symptoms have been described for much of recorded history, the first clearly documented case occurred in 1894.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Although about 50% of women with BV are asymptomatic, common symptoms include increased vaginal discharge that usually smells like fish.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The discharge coats the walls of the vagina, and is usually without significant irritation, pain, or erythema, although mild itching can sometimes occur.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] By contrast, the normal vaginal discharge will vary in consistency and amount throughout the menstrual cycle and is at its clearest at ovulation—about two weeks before the period starts.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Some practitioners claim that BV can be asymptomatic in almost half of affected women, though others argue that this is often a misdiagnosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Although previously considered a mere nuisance infection, untreated bacterial vaginosis may cause increased susceptibility to sexually transmitted infections, including HIV, and pregnancy complications.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] It has been shown that HIV-infected women with bacterial vaginosis (BV) are more likely to transmit HIV to their sexual partners than those without BV.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] There is evidence of an association between BV and increased rates of sexually transmitted infections such as HIV/AIDS.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is associated with up to a six-fold increase in HIV shedding.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is a risk factor for viral shedding and herpes simplex virus type 2 infection.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV may increase the risk of infection with or reactivation of human papillomavirus (HPV).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] In addition, bacterial vaginosis, as either pre-existing, or acquired, may increase the risk of pregnancy complications, most notably premature birth or miscarriage.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Pregnant women with BV have a higher risk of chorioamnionitis, miscarriage, preterm birth, premature rupture of membranes, and postpartum endometritis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Women with BV who are treated with in vitro fertilization have a lower implantation rate and higher rates of early pregnancy loss.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Healthy vaginal microbiota consists of species that neither cause symptoms or infections, nor negatively affect pregnancy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] It is dominated mainly by Lactobacillus species.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is defined by the disequilibrium in the vaginal microbiota, with decline in the number of lactobacilli.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] While the infection involves several bacteria, it is believed that most infections start with *Gardnerella vaginalis* creating a biofilm, which allows other opportunistic bacteria, such as *Prevotella* and *Bacteroides*, to thrive.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] One of the main risks for developing BV is douching, which alters the vaginal microbiota and predisposes women to developing BV.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Douching is strongly discouraged by the U.S.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Department of Health and Human Services and various medical authorities, for this and other reasons.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is a risk factor for pelvic inflammatory disease, HIV, sexually transmitted infections (STIs), endometriosis, and reproductive and obstetric disorders or negative outcomes.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Although BV can be associated with sexual activity, there is no clear evidence of sexual transmission.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] It is possible for sexually inactive persons to develop bacterial vaginosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Subclinical iron deficiency may correlate with bacterial vaginosis in early pregnancy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] A longitudinal study published in February 2006, in the *American Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology*, showed a link between psychosocial stress and bacterial vaginosis persisted even when other risk factors were taken into account.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Exposure to the spermicide nonoxynol-9 does not affect the risk of developing bacterial vaginosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The cause of the fishy smell of BV is mainly due to reduction of trimethylamine oxide (TMAO) to trimethylamine (TMA) by bacteria in vaginal secretion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] TMA is the same compound that is predominantly responsible for the smell of decomposing fish.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The diamines putrescine and cadaverine, which are the decarboxylation products of arginine and lysine amino acid metabolism, respectively, are also present in BV and may contribute to the fishy smell of the condition as well.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] To make a diagnosis of bacterial vaginosis, a swab from inside the vagina should be obtained.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) defines STIs as "a variety of clinical syndromes and infections caused by pathogens that can be acquired and transmitted through sexual activity." But the CDC does not specifically identify BV as a sexually transmitted infection.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Release of a fishy odor on adding alkali—10% potassium hydroxide (KOH) solution.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] At least three of the four criteria should be present for a confirmed diagnosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] A modification of the Amsel criteria accepts the presence of two instead of three factors and is considered equally diagnostic.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] An alternative is to use a Gram-stained vaginal smear, with the Hay/Ison criteria or the Nugent criteria.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The Nugent score is now rarely used by physicians due to the time it takes to read the slides and requires the use of a trained microscopist.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] A score of 0–10 is generated from combining three other scores.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] At least 10–20 high power (1000× oil immersion) fields are counted and an average determined.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] DNA hybridization testing with Affirm VPIII was compared to the Gram stain using the Nugent criteria.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The Affirm VPIII test may be used for the rapid diagnosis of BV in symptomatic women but uses expensive proprietary equipment to read results, and does not detect other pathogens that cause BV, including *Prevotella* spp, *Bacteroides* spp, and *Mobiluncus* spp.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The cervicovaginal microbiome measured using 16S rRNA sequencing has the capacity to increase throughput of the Nugent Score and has demonstrate to be directly comparable to clinical Nugent Score measurement.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Some steps suggested to lower the risk include not douching, not using perfumed soaps and limiting the number of sex partners.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Systematic reviews and meta-analyses from 2022 to 2023 have concluded that probiotics may help prevent re-occurrence.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Early evidence suggested that antibiotic treatment of male partners could re-establish the normal microbiota of the male urogenital tract and prevent the recurrence of infection.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] However, a 2016 Cochrane review found high-quality evidence that treating the sexual partners of women with bacterial vaginosis had no effect on symptoms, clinical outcomes, or recurrence in the affected women.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] It also found that such treatment may lead treated sexual partners to report increased adverse events.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Treatment is typically with the antibiotics metronidazole or clindamycin.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] They can be either given by mouth or applied inside the vagina with similar efficacy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Other antibiotics related to metronidazole, including tinidazole and the newer secnidazole, are also approved and used to treat BV.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] When clindamycin is given to pregnant women symptomatic with BV before 22 weeks of gestation the risk of pre-term birth before 37 weeks of gestation is lower.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Additional antibiotics that are not approved for treatment of BV but might work include macrolides, lincosamides, and penicillins.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Although antibiotics are effective, about 10% to 15% of people do not improve with the first course of antibiotics, and recurrence rates of up to 80% have been documented.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Recurrence rates are increased with sexual activity with the same pre-/post-treatment partner and inconsistent condom use.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is not considered a sexually transmitted infection, and antibiotic treatment of a male sexual partner of a woman with BV is not recommended.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Topical antiseptics, for example dequalinium chloride, policresulen, hexetidine, povidone-iodine, or boric acid vaginal suppositories may be applied, if the risk of ascending infections is low (outside of pregnancy and in immunocompetent people without histories of upper genital tract infections).
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Dequalinium chloride is available as a prescription vaginal tablet, for instance in Europe and Canada, is given as a 6-day course, and is non-inferior to metronidazole in the treatment of bacterial vaginosis.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Povidone-iodine is approved as a vaginal gel to treat bacterial vaginosis under the brand name Astrodimer, among others.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] One study found that vaginal irrigations with hydrogen peroxide (3%) resulted in a slight improvement, but this was much less than with the use of oral metronidazole.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Dequalinium chloride and povidone-iodine (as Astrodimer) have the best evidence of effectiveness.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Neither of these are available in the United States, though they are available in other countries.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Intravaginal boric acid, alone or in conjunction with other medications, may be helpful in the treatment of recurrent BV.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] TOL-463, an experimental formulation of boric acid enhanced with ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA), is under development as an intravaginal medication for the treatment of BV and has shown preliminary effectiveness in clinical trials.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] A 2009 Cochrane review found tentative but insufficient evidence for probiotics as a treatment for BV.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] A 2014 review reached the same conclusion.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] A 2013 review found some evidence supporting the use of probiotics during pregnancy.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The preferred probiotics for BV are those containing high doses of lactobacilli (around 109 CFUsTooltip Colony-forming units) given in the vagina.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Intravaginal administration is preferred to taking them by mouth.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Prolonged repetitive courses of treatment appear to be more promising than short courses.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The lack of effectiveness of commercially available *Lactobacillus* probiotics may be because most do not contain vaginal lactobacilli strains.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] LACTIN-V is a live biopharmaceutical medication containing the vaginally important *Lactobacillus crispatus* which is under development for the treatment of bacterial vaginosis and recurrent urinary tract infections.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] It has shown initial effectiveness in considerably reducing recurrence of bacterial vaginosis following antibiotic treatment.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] LACTIN-V is not yet Food and Drug Administration (FDA)-approved or commercially available.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Estrogen-containing contraceptives have been found to decrease recurrence of BV.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is the most common infection of the vagina in women of reproductive age.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] The percentage of women affected at any given time varies between 5% and 70%.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] BV is most common in parts of Africa, and least common in Asia and Europe.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] In the United States, about 30% of those between the ages of 14 and 49 are affected.
[src:bacterial-vaginosis/bacterial-vaginosis] Rates vary considerably between ethnic groups within a country.
